Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Trim the @butternut squash{1}, halve lengthways, then scoop out the seeds (peel first if you prefer). Cut into 2cm chunks and pop onto a large #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{to taste}, toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and cooked through, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, pour the @water for the rice{200%ml} into a medium #saucepan{} with a #tight-fitting lid{}.

Stir in the @jasmine rice{100%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest and cut the @lime{1} into wedges.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the garlic, @Thai green style paste{45%g} and @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} (add less if you prefer things milder). Stir-fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Once fragrant, stir in the @king prawns{150%g}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @coconut milk{200%ml} then bring to a boil. Turn the heat down and simmer, stirring occasionally, until thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

When thickened, stir the @peas{120%g} into the curry and cook until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Remove from the heat. Season with @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and a squeeze of lime juice from a lime wedge.

Once the butternut squash is ready, pop the curry back on medium heat. Add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir the butternut into the curry, adding a splash of @water{if needed} if it's a little too thick.

Taste the curry and season with more salt, pepper or lime juice if needed.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once everything's ready, fluff up the rice using a #fork{}. Stir through the lime zest then share it out between your #bowls{}.

Spoon the Thai green style curry over the zesty rice and top with the @crispy onions{1%sachet}.

Serve with any remaining lime wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!